The dataset used here is part of larger dataset that consists of questions regarding learning approaches. It consists of 7 variables: 2 demographic (gender, age), 3 measuring learning approaches (deep learning, surface learning, strategic learning), attitude towards statistics, and exam points in a statistics course. Learning approach variables and attitude are combination variables averaged from multiple questions measuring the same dimension. When dropping rows with 0 exam points, there is total of 166 observations. Gender is character type and is changed to factor type due to upcoming analyses. Other variables are integer or numeric type.

Fitting multiple regression model

I selected attitude as explaining variable because of its highest correlation with exam points. In addition I included gender and age as to the model to see if demographic variables have any statistical relationship to exam points.

model1 <- lm(points ~ gender + age + attitude, data = lrn14_sub)

The first fitted model had only one statistically significant explanatory variable, attention. Gender and age had no statistically significant relationship to exam points (p-values clearly over 0.05). Therefore, second model were created where the variable with weakest relationship to exam points (gender) was dropped.

model2 <- lm(points ~ age + attitude, data = lrn14_sub)

As we can see from the results, dropping gender out from the model did not change much the results regarding age, which is still not even close to statistical significance (p = 0.144). Thus, age was also dropped and third model was created with only attention as explanatory variable.

model3 <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = lrn14_sub)
summary(model3)

Here we can see our final model with only one explanatory variable, attention towards statistics. It has clear statistical relationship to exam points with very low p-value. In addition, seen from R-squared values of the model, attention towards statistics is able to explain around 19 % of the variance in exam points. This is not surprising, because it was expected that attention towards statistics is somehow related to statistics exam scores.

Diagnostic plots

Because I created multiple models, I will produce the diagnostic plots for the starting point (model 1) and the final model (model 3). The regression model assumptions inspected here are constant variance and linearity, normality (of residuals) and lack of too influential outliers.

plot(model1, which = c(1,2,5))

plot(model3, which = c(1,2,5))

As can be seen from the plots, these two models do not differ much from each other in model diagnostics. Residual vs fitted plot shows that aside 3 (kind of) outliers, the variance is quite constant across fitted values. There is some decrease in variance when fitted values are high, but this is based on just few observations so I don’t see it as a big problem. Q-Q plot do not show clear deviance from normality. It is normal to see some deviance in end points and this does not pose any real problem for model assumptions. The residuals vs leverage plot does show us that there are no single outliers that are too influential to the model. Overall, based on visual inspection of diagnostic plots, assumptions for regression model were not violated.

The dataset consists of demographical information (including alcohol consumption) and student grades collected from two secondary education subjects (mathematics and Portuguese language) over 3 periods. The dataset has 35 variables and 370 observations.

Selecting variables and presenting hypothesis

For studying high alcohol consumption, I will select romantic relationship status, weekly study time, final grade, and number of school absences for predictors.

vars <- c("romantic", "studytime", "G3", "absences", "high_use")

My hypothesis is that absence of romantic relationship, low weekly study time, low final grade, and high number of school absences are risk factors for heavy alcohol use.

Distributions of the chosen variables and their relationships

data <- select(alc, all_of(vars)) # Create data with only chosen variables

- The cross-tabulations between romantic and high_use, we can see that the relationship between these variables is not immediately clear. There are more participants who are not in relationship, but in both groups the proportion of heavy alcohol users seems to be around the same. - The cross-tabulation between studytime and high_use, in turn, reveals clear relationship between time spent in studying and use of alcohol. Most of the participants study 2-5 hours or less. - The boxplot between final grades and alcohol use reveals little bit lower average scores in high alcohol use group when compared to low alcohol use group. As an important notion, the variance is also smaller in high alcohol users. - The boxplot between number of school absences and alcohol use reveals that in high alcohol users group there are more school absences on average than in low alcohol users group. In both groups the distribution is highly skewed, which is not surprising. - The inspection of cross-tabulations and boxplots gives tentative support for my hypothesis, with the exception of romantic relationship.

Logistic regression

According to model summary, higher number of absences and less study time are statistically related to heavy alcohol use. Final grade scores and romantic relationship are not statistically related to heavy alcohol use after accounting for effects of number of absences and study time. Inspecting odds ratios and their confidence intervals shows same story. The odds of people having x+1 number of absence being heavy alcohol users is between about 104% and 113% of the odds of people having x number of absence. Also, the odds of people in one higher study time category being heavy alcohol users is between about 43% and 80% of the odds of people in one lower study time category.

Predictive power of the model with only statistically significant predictors

model2 <- glm(high_use ~ studytime + absences, data = data, family = "binomial") # model with only statistically significant predictors
probabilities <- predict(model2, type = "response")
data <- mutate(data, probability = probabilities)
data <- mutate(data, prediction = probability > 0.5)
table(high_use = data$high_use, prediction = data$prediction) %>% prop.table() %>% addmargins()
##         prediction
## high_use      FALSE       TRUE        Sum
##    FALSE 0.67027027 0.02972973 0.70000000
##    TRUE  0.25135135 0.04864865 0.30000000
##    Sum   0.92162162 0.07837838 1.00000000

The model seems to classify most of the cases correctly and clearly better than just by simple guessing strategy. However, there are around 30% of incorrectly classified cases.

Test and train datasets

bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE)
boston_scaled$crim <- crime

n <- nrow(boston_scaled)
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

Linear discriminant analysis

lda.fit <- lda(crim ~ ., data = train)

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

classes <- as.numeric(train$crim)

plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

Looks like rad (index of accessibility to radial highways) has quite strongly its own dimension whereas other dimensions are more grouped together.

Predict crime classes with the LDA model

correct_classes <- test$crim
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crim)

lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)
##                  predicted
## correct           [-0.419,-0.411] (-0.411,-0.39] (-0.39,0.00739] (0.00739,9.92]
##   [-0.419,-0.411]              14              6               3              0
##   (-0.411,-0.39]                4             11               5              0
##   (-0.39,0.00739]               1             10              13              2
##   (0.00739,9.92]                0              0               1             32

The model predicts most of the classes correctly, and when it does not, it usually predicts the observation to neighbour classes. The extreme classes are predicted little bit better than the middle classes.

Clustering the data

First with 3 clusters.

boston_scaled <- scale(Boston)
boston_scaled <- as.data.frame(boston_scaled) # data frame

dist_eu <- dist(boston_scaled, method = "euclidean")
dist_man <- dist(boston_scaled, method = "manhattan")

km <- kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 3)
pairs(boston_scaled, col = km$cluster)

With 4 clusters.

km <- kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 4)
pairs(boston_scaled, col = km$cluster)

With 5 clusters.

km <- kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 5)
pairs(boston_scaled, col = km$cluster)

Visually it seems that the best amount of clusters is 4. With 5 clusters there are too much overlapping and some clusters do not have clear groups in any of the bivariate scatterplots.

Lets check if this interpretation holds with total within sum of squares analysis.

k_max <- 5

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_scaled, k)$tot.withinss})

qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')
## Warning: `qplot()` was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.

By visual inspection of the total within sum of squares plot, it seems that optimal number of clusters is probably 3.

Bonus

boston_scaled <- scale(Boston)
boston_scaled <- as.data.frame(boston_scaled) # data frame

km <- kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 3)
boston_scaled$cluster <- km$cluster

lda.fit <- lda(cluster ~ ., data = boston_scaled)

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

It seems that nox (nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)), tax (full-value property-tax rate per $10,000), age (proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940), and zn (proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft) are most influential variables on the 3 cluster model used here.
